Oh, let's do something simpler first.

2242
01:27:41,640 --> 01:27:44,640
Let's do the muon decay.

2243
01:27:44,640 --> 01:27:47,640
The muon is also something that can decay.

2244
01:27:47,640 --> 01:27:49,640
So let's take the muon.

2245
01:27:49,640 --> 01:27:51,640
Here's the muon moving along.

2246
01:27:51,640 --> 01:27:53,640
Now what can the muon do?

2247
01:27:53,640 --> 01:27:58,640
The muon can become a neutrino submuon

2248
01:27:58,640 --> 01:28:00,640
and emit a W.

2249
01:28:00,640 --> 01:28:03,640
What kind of W? W minus, right?

2250
01:28:05,640 --> 01:28:08,640
It can become a W minus and a neutrino.

2251
01:28:08,640 --> 01:28:11,140
But now one of the

2252
01:28:11,140 --> 01:28:13,640
things a W minus can do

2253
01:28:13,640 --> 01:28:17,640
is it can become an electron and an antineutrino.

2254
01:28:17,640 --> 01:28:22,640
So this W minus can now become an electron

2255
01:28:22,640 --> 01:28:27,640
and an antineutrino of the electron variety.

2256
01:28:27,640 --> 01:28:29,640
Can this happen?

2257
01:28:29,640 --> 01:28:32,640
The only thing that would... Yes, it can happen.

2258
01:28:32,640 --> 01:28:34,140
Not only can it happen, this

2259
01:28:34,140 --> 01:28:35,640
is the way the muon decays.

2260
01:28:35,640 --> 01:28:37,640
The muon decays,

2261
01:28:38,640 --> 01:28:41,640
because it is sufficiently much heavier

2262
01:28:43,640 --> 01:28:45,640
than the electron,

2263
01:28:45,640 --> 01:28:47,640
much heavier than the electron,

2264
01:28:47,640 --> 01:28:50,640
about 200 times heavier than the electron.

2265
01:28:50,640 --> 01:28:52,640
The neutrinos are practically massless,

2266
01:28:52,640 --> 01:28:54,640
so the energy balance is

2267
01:28:54,640 --> 01:28:56,640
you have about 100 MeV here,

2268
01:28:56,640 --> 01:28:57,640
a half an MeV here,

2269
01:28:57,640 --> 01:28:59,640
and the rest goes off in kinetic energy.

2270
01:28:59,640 --> 01:29:01,640
So that's an example of a...

2271
01:29:01,640 --> 01:29:04,640
what's called a purely leptonic process.

2272
01:29:04,640 --> 01:29:06,640
No quarks in it at all.

2273
01:29:06,640 --> 01:29:08,640
Is that an antineutrino?

2274
01:29:08,640 --> 01:29:09,640
Is it what?

2275
01:29:09,640 --> 01:29:10,640
An antielectron.

2276
01:29:10,640 --> 01:29:12,640
Yeah, it is.

2277
01:29:12,640 --> 01:29:14,640
Right.

2278
01:29:14,640 --> 01:29:18,640
So it's one neutrino, one antineutrino, and an electron.

2279
01:29:18,640 --> 01:29:20,640
Okay? So that happens.

2280
01:29:20,640 --> 01:29:24,640
And that's the primary decay.

2281
01:29:24,640 --> 01:29:27,640
It's the only decay of the muon.

2282
01:29:27,640 --> 01:29:30,640
So the muon is an unstable particle because of this,

2283
01:29:30,640 --> 01:29:32,140
but the reason the muon

2284
01:29:32,140 --> 01:29:33,640
is unstable and not the electron

2285
01:29:33,640 --> 01:29:35,640
is just that the muon happens to be heavy enough

2286
01:29:35,640 --> 01:29:37,640
to be able to decay to the electron.

2287
01:29:37,640 --> 01:29:39,640
The electron is not heavy

2288
01:29:39,640 --> 01:29:41,640
enough to decay to the muon.

2289
01:29:41,640 --> 01:29:45,640
So in a sense, it's an accident of the masses.

2290
01:29:45,640 --> 01:29:47,640
The same is true of the tau, incidentally.

2291
01:29:47,640 --> 01:29:52,640
The tau can also decay to other leptons.

2292
01:29:52,640 --> 01:29:55,640
But, all right, that's the mu decay.

2293
01:29:55,640 --> 01:29:58,640
And notice the components are the same.

2294
01:29:58,640 --> 01:30:00,640
The basic components are the same.

2295
01:30:00,640 --> 01:30:03,640
A transition from one column to another,

2296
01:30:03,640 --> 01:30:05,640
followed by a W,

2297
01:30:05,640 --> 01:30:08,640
and then the W makes another transition

2298
01:30:08,640 --> 01:30:10,640
from one column to the other.

2299
01:30:10,640 --> 01:30:12,640
Or, if you like, a decay

2300
01:30:12,640 --> 01:30:14,640
from one column to the other.

2301
01:30:14,640 --> 01:30:19,640
All right, what about the decay of the neutron?

2302
01:30:19,640 --> 01:30:21,640
Decay of the neutron...

2303
01:30:21,640 --> 01:30:23,640
Would it be consistent to say

2304
01:30:23,640 --> 01:30:26,640
the purpose of a linear accelerator, per se,

2305
01:30:26,640 --> 01:30:29,640
is to effectively increase the mass of the electron

2306
01:30:29,640 --> 01:30:32,640
so that it can now go the other direction?

2307
01:30:32,640 --> 01:30:33,640
Absolutely.

2308
01:30:33,640 --> 01:30:34,640
Yeah.

2309
01:30:35,640 --> 01:30:37,640
Yeah.

2310
01:30:37,640 --> 01:30:38,640
I mean, you don't change the mass,

2311
01:30:38,640 --> 01:30:39,640
you just put enough energy in it.

2312
01:30:39,640 --> 01:30:40,640
You put enough energy...

2313
01:30:40,640 --> 01:30:41,640
Absolutely.

2314
01:30:41,640 --> 01:30:43,640
Yeah, that's exactly right.

2315
01:30:43,640 --> 01:30:45,640
Okay, we were going to do neutron decay.

2316
01:30:45,640 --> 01:30:47,640
So the neutron is...

2317
01:30:47,640 --> 01:30:50,640
Maybe I'd better switch to vertical.

2318
01:30:50,640 --> 01:30:52,640
I don't want to...

2319
01:30:52,640 --> 01:30:53,640
Vertical.

2320
01:30:53,640 --> 01:30:55,640
Vertical notation, back to vertical.

2321
01:30:55,640 --> 01:30:58,640
Neutron is three quarks,

2322
01:30:58,640 --> 01:31:00,640
two down quarks,

2323
01:31:00,640 --> 01:31:02,640
and an up quark.

2324
01:31:02,640 --> 01:31:04,640
Right?

2325
01:31:04,640 --> 01:31:05,640
Minus...

2326
01:31:05,640 --> 01:31:08,640
Minus four thirds plus two thirds...

2327
01:31:08,640 --> 01:31:09,640
Sorry, minus two thirds...

2328
01:31:09,640 --> 01:31:11,640
Yes, that's a neutron.

2329
01:31:11,640 --> 01:31:13,640
Electrically neutral.

2330
01:31:13,640 --> 01:31:15,640
Neutron coming in.

2331
01:31:15,640 --> 01:31:18,640
Okay, now what is possible?

2332
01:31:18,640 --> 01:31:21,640
First of all, we can have the up quark

2333
01:31:21,640 --> 01:31:23,640
become a down quark

2334
01:31:23,640 --> 01:31:25,640
and emit some sort of W.

2335
01:31:25,640 --> 01:31:29,640
But that'll give us three down quarks.

2336
01:31:29,640 --> 01:31:31,640
Three down quarks is a fine thing.

2337
01:31:31,640 --> 01:31:33,640
There's nothing wrong with three down quarks,

2338
01:31:33,640 --> 01:31:35,640
except that the mass of the neutron

2339
01:31:35,640 --> 01:31:38,640
is less than three down quarks.

2340
01:31:38,640 --> 01:31:40,640
The mass of three down quarks,

2341
01:31:40,640 --> 01:31:43,640
of a particle with three down quarks,

2342
01:31:43,640 --> 01:31:46,640
is always too heavy for the neutron to decay.

2343
01:31:46,640 --> 01:31:48,640
So that's not what happens.

2344
01:31:48,640 --> 01:31:50,640
What about one of the down quarks?

2345
01:31:50,640 --> 01:31:55,640
The down quark can emit a W,

2346
01:31:55,640 --> 01:31:59,640
become an up quark.

2347
01:31:59,640 --> 01:32:02,640
This is again a W minus.

2348
01:32:02,640 --> 01:32:04,640
The down quark emits a W minus,

2349
01:32:04,640 --> 01:32:06,640
and that's a down quark.

2350
01:32:06,640 --> 01:32:08,640
And now we have two up quarks

2351
01:32:08,640 --> 01:32:09,640
and a down quark.

2352
01:32:09,640 --> 01:32:11,640
Up, up, down.

2353
01:32:11,640 --> 01:32:12,640
What is that called?

2354
01:32:12,640 --> 01:32:13,640
Proton.

2355
01:32:13,640 --> 01:32:15,640
That's a proton.

2356
01:32:17,640 --> 01:32:21,640
And the W does what the W always does.

2357
01:32:21,640 --> 01:32:25,640
It decays to an electron

2358
01:32:25,640 --> 01:32:28,640
and an anti-neutrino.

2359
01:32:30,640 --> 01:32:33,640
Electron, anti-neutrino.

2360
01:32:33,640 --> 01:32:38,640
So that's the beta decay of the neutron.

2361
01:32:38,640 --> 01:32:41,640
Could it decay into a muon in a neutrino?

2362
01:32:44,640 --> 01:32:45,640
Not enough energy.

2363
01:32:45,640 --> 01:32:47,640
The muon is too heavy

2364
01:32:47,640 --> 01:32:50,640
so that there wouldn't be enough energy left over

2365
01:32:50,640 --> 01:32:52,640
for the muon.

2366
01:32:52,640 --> 01:32:53,640
But other than that,

2367
01:32:53,640 --> 01:32:54,640
if it were not for that,

2368
01:32:54,640 --> 01:32:55,640
it could happen.

2369
01:32:55,640 --> 01:32:57,640
Another way to say it is if you could

2370
01:32:57,640 --> 01:33:01,640
jam some more energy into the neutron.

2371
01:33:01,640 --> 01:33:02,640
How can you do it?

2372
01:33:02,640 --> 01:33:03,640
You give it a shove.

2373
01:33:03,640 --> 01:33:05,640
You give the neutron a whack,

2374
01:33:05,640 --> 01:33:06,640
you excite it,

2375
01:33:06,640 --> 01:33:08,640
and if you excite it enough,

2376
01:33:08,640 --> 01:33:10,640
it can decay to a proton,

2377
01:33:10,640 --> 01:33:12,640
a neutrino, anti-neutrino, and a muon.

2378
01:33:12,640 --> 01:33:15,640
But without somehow providing that extra energy,

2379
01:33:15,640 --> 01:33:19,640
the neutron will only decay to the proton,

2380
01:33:19,640 --> 01:33:21,640
electron, and anti-neutrino.

2381
01:33:23,640 --> 01:33:24,640
Okay, now let's come...

2382
01:33:24,640 --> 01:33:25,640
Let's see, where are we?

2383
01:33:25,640 --> 01:33:27,640
I think we're finished for tonight.

2384
01:33:27,640 --> 01:33:28,640
I think we're finished for tonight.

2385
01:33:28,640 --> 01:33:30,640
But remember, we have a puzzle.

2386
01:33:30,640 --> 01:33:31,640
And the puzzle is,

2387
01:33:31,640 --> 01:33:36,640
why is it that the weak interactions

2388
01:33:36,640 --> 01:33:39,640
give such slow decay rates?

2389
01:33:39,640 --> 01:33:44,640
And I can think of one reason,

2390
01:33:44,640 --> 01:33:48,640
namely, the coupling constant,

2391
01:33:48,640 --> 01:33:53,640
or the analog of the fine structure constant,

2392
01:33:53,640 --> 01:33:55,640
could be ridiculously small,

2393
01:33:55,640 --> 01:33:58,640
so that the probability of emitting these W bosons

2394
01:33:58,640 --> 01:34:00,640
would be very, very small.

2395
01:34:00,640 --> 01:34:02,640
That is not the reason.

2396
01:34:02,640 --> 01:34:05,640
The fine structure constant for the weak interactions

2397
01:34:05,640 --> 01:34:07,640
is about the same as for electromagnetism.

2398
01:34:07,640 --> 01:34:09,640
That is not the reason.

2399
01:34:09,640 --> 01:34:10,640
The reason is something else,

2400
01:34:10,640 --> 01:34:12,640
and we'll come to the something else next time.

2401
01:34:12,640 --> 01:34:14,640
Yeah?

2402
01:34:14,640 --> 01:34:18,640
When you say that theory has its own truth,

2403
01:34:18,640 --> 01:34:20,640
you mean that the Lagrangian...

2404
01:34:20,640 --> 01:34:25,640
The Lagrangian is invariant under those operations.

2405
01:34:25,640 --> 01:34:26,640
That's exactly what it means.

2406
01:34:26,640 --> 01:34:29,640
I didn't want to start writing bunches of Lagrangians,

2407
01:34:29,640 --> 01:34:31,140
so I've used the shorthand

2408
01:34:31,140 --> 01:34:32,640
of saying there's a symmetry, right?

2409
01:34:32,640 --> 01:34:35,640
But that's what it means, yeah.

2410
01:34:35,640 --> 01:34:40,640
For more, please visit us at stanford.edu.

